From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000000 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: gregordinary <33880035+gregordinary@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Mon, 14 Jul 2026 12:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] rocket: make the submit ioctl's uAPI structs extensible

drm_rocket_submit carries @job_struct_size and drm_rocket_job carries
@task_struct_size so that the descriptors can grow: userspace declares the size
of the struct it was built against and the kernel copies what it understands.
Both size checks currently defeat that by comparing against the kernel's own
sizeof:

	if (args->job_struct_size < sizeof(struct drm_rocket_job))
		return -EINVAL;
	if (job->task_struct_size < sizeof(struct drm_rocket_task))
		return -EINVAL;

So the day either struct gains a field, every already-built userspace -- which
still declares the smaller, original size -- starts failing SUBMIT with -EINVAL.
The size fields promise forward compatibility the code does not honor. Nothing
in-tree grows the structs yet, so this is latent today; it is a loaded gun for
the next uAPI addition, and appending a field is exactly what a uAPI is for.

The copy has the mirror-image problem. copy_from_user() always reads the
kernel's sizeof(), so a userspace NEWER than the kernel has its trailing fields
read past the end of what it supplied (when its struct is shorter) or, once a
short-struct check is relaxed, has fields it did set silently ignored -- a flag
the kernel never looked at, running a job with semantics nobody asked for.

Use the kernel's standard extensible-struct contract instead:

  - Guard on the ORIGINAL ("v1") layout via offsetofend() -- the minimum a
    caller must supply -- rather than on the current sizeof(). An older,
    shorter userspace keeps working against a grown struct.

  - Copy with copy_struct_from_user(), which copies min(usize, ksize),
    zero-fills the fields the caller did not supply, and returns -E2BIG if
    userspace set anything in a trailing field this kernel does not know about.
    A newer userspace's request is refused loudly instead of being silently
    downgraded.

With both in place, appending a field to drm_rocket_job or drm_rocket_task needs
no further change here: add the field, leave the v1 guard alone, and old and new
userspace both keep working in both directions.

While here, fix a latent NULL dereference this makes reachable. A submit that
fails before rocket_iommu_domain_get() (a bad BO handle, a rejected task) reaches
rocket_job_cleanup() with job->domain still NULL from the kzalloc, and
rocket_iommu_domain_put() dereferenced it unconditionally -- a kernel oops any
client can trigger with one malformed submit. Guard it to no-op on NULL, like
kfree(). Reporting the per-job error (above) is what first makes this path
routinely exercised, so the two belong together.

Also declare the interface version. drm_driver leaves .major/.minor unset, so
stock rocket reports 0.0.0 through DRM_IOCTL_VERSION and userspace has no way to
ask what the kernel guarantees. Advertise 1.0 to mean exactly the contract above:
"the submit descriptors are extensible, and a field I do not know is an -E2BIG,
not a silent drop." Userspace can then require >= 1.0 before relying on it, and
a later feature can claim 1.1 (the batched-submit patch does).

No ABI change: neither struct grows here, and for today's layouts
offsetofend(v1 tail) == sizeof(), so the accepted/rejected set is unchanged.
This is the precondition for any patch that DOES grow them (see the batched-submit
patch, which adds drm_rocket_job.flags).

Apply on top of the bo-mm-uaf fix.
---
drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c | 23 ++++++++++++--
drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_job.c | 67 +++++++++++++++++++++++++++++++--------
2 files changed, 73 insertions(+), 17 deletions(-)

diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
index 0cf785d..728e7a0 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_drv.c
@@ -167,7 +167,16 @@ rocket_iommu_domain_get(struct rocket_file_priv *rocket_priv)
 void
 rocket_iommu_domain_put(struct rocket_iommu_domain *domain)
 {
-	kref_put(&domain->kref, rocket_iommu_domain_destroy);
+	/*
+	 * Tolerate NULL like kfree()/dma_fence_put() do. rocket_job_cleanup()
+	 * calls this unconditionally, but a job that fails in rocket_ioctl_submit_job
+	 * before rocket_iommu_domain_get() (a bad BO handle, a rejected task) reaches
+	 * cleanup with job->domain still NULL from the kzalloc. Without this guard
+	 * that path dereferences NULL and oopses the kernel -- a crash any client can
+	 * trigger with one malformed submit.
+	 */
+	if (domain)
+		kref_put(&domain->kref, rocket_iommu_domain_destroy);
 }
 
 static int
@@ -239,10 +248,18 @@ static const struct drm_ioctl_desc rocket_drm_driver_ioctls[] = {
 DEFINE_DRM_ACCEL_FOPS(rocket_accel_driver_fops);
 
 /*
- * Rocket driver version:
- * - 1.0 - initial interface
+ * Rocket driver version. Stock leaves .major/.minor unset, so a driver that has
+ * not been told to advertise anything reports 0.0.0; userspace reads this to
+ * decide what the kernel guarantees.
+ *
+ * - 1.0 - initial interface, with EXTENSIBLE submit descriptors: drm_rocket_job
+ *         and drm_rocket_task may be extended, the kernel accepts any size from
+ *         the v1 layout upward, and a trailing field this kernel does not know
+ *         is refused with -E2BIG rather than silently ignored.
  */
 static const struct drm_driver rocket_drm_driver = {
+	.major			= 1,
+	.minor			= 0,
 	.driver_features	= DRIVER_COMPUTE_ACCEL | DRIVER_GEM,
 	.open			= rocket_open,
 	.postclose		= rocket_postclose,
diff --git a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_job.c b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_job.c
index d01b746..cbc90da 100644
--- a/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_job.c
+++ b/drivers/accel/rocket/rocket_job.c
@@ -12,6 +12,8 @@
 #include <linux/kref.h>
 #include <linux/platform_device.h>
 #include <linux/pm_runtime.h>
+#include <linux/stddef.h>
+#include <linux/uaccess.h>
 
 #include "rocket_core.h"
 #include "rocket_device.h"
@@ -21,6 +23,30 @@
 
 #define JOB_TIMEOUT_MS 500
 
+/*
+ * The submit ioctl's descriptors (drm_rocket_job, drm_rocket_task) are
+ * EXTENSIBLE: userspace declares the size of the struct it was built against
+ * (@job_struct_size / @task_struct_size) and the kernel accepts any size from
+ * the original ("v1") layout upward. That is the whole point of those size
+ * fields, and it only works if the kernel asks for the v1 MINIMUM rather than
+ * its own current sizeof:
+ *
+ *   - A kernel whose struct has grown must still accept an older, shorter
+ *     userspace. Comparing against sizeof() rejects it with -EINVAL, so the
+ *     moment a field is appended every pre-existing binary stops working.
+ *   - A userspace newer than the kernel must not have its extra fields
+ *     silently dropped: a flag the kernel never read would run a job with
+ *     semantics nobody asked for.
+ *
+ * copy_struct_from_user() is the kernel's standard answer to both: it copies
+ * min(usize, ksize), zero-fills the fields the caller did not supply, and
+ * returns -E2BIG if userspace set anything in a trailing field this kernel does
+ * not know about. Growing either struct therefore needs no change here -- add
+ * the field, keep the v1 offsetofend() guard, and both directions keep working.
+ */
+#define ROCKET_JOB_V1_SIZE   offsetofend(struct drm_rocket_job, out_bo_handle_count)
+#define ROCKET_TASK_V1_SIZE  offsetofend(struct drm_rocket_task, regcmd_count)
+
 static struct rocket_job *
 to_rocket_job(struct drm_sched_job *sched_job)
 {
@@ -64,7 +90,7 @@ rocket_copy_tasks(struct drm_device *dev,
 {
 	int ret = 0;
 
-	if (job->task_struct_size < sizeof(struct drm_rocket_task))
+	if (job->task_struct_size < ROCKET_TASK_V1_SIZE)
 		return -EINVAL;
 
 	rjob->task_count = job->task_count;
@@ -81,11 +107,12 @@ rocket_copy_tasks(struct drm_device *dev,
 	for (int i = 0; i < rjob->task_count; i++) {
 		struct drm_rocket_task task = {0};
 
-		if (copy_from_user(&task,
-				   u64_to_user_ptr(job->tasks) + i * job->task_struct_size,
-				   sizeof(task))) {
-			drm_dbg(dev, "Failed to copy incoming tasks\n");
-			ret = -EFAULT;
+		ret = copy_struct_from_user(&task, sizeof(task),
+					    u64_to_user_ptr(job->tasks) +
+						    i * job->task_struct_size,
+					    job->task_struct_size);
+		if (ret) {
+			drm_dbg(dev, "Failed to copy incoming tasks (%d)\n", ret);
 			goto fail;
 		}
 
@@ -633,7 +660,7 @@ int rocket_ioctl_submit(struct drm_device *dev, void *data, struct drm_file *fil
 	if (args->job_count == 0)
 		return 0;
 
-	if (args->job_struct_size < sizeof(struct drm_rocket_job)) {
+	if (args->job_struct_size < ROCKET_JOB_V1_SIZE) {
 		drm_dbg(dev, "job_struct_size field in drm_rocket_submit struct is too small.\n");
 		return -EINVAL;
 	}
@@ -650,18 +677,30 @@ int rocket_ioctl_submit(struct drm_device *dev, void *data, struct drm_file *fil
 	}
 
 	for (i = 0; i < args->job_count; i++) {
-		if (copy_from_user(&jobs[i],
-				   u64_to_user_ptr(args->jobs) + i * args->job_struct_size,
-				   sizeof(*jobs))) {
-			ret = -EFAULT;
-			drm_dbg(dev, "Failed to copy incoming job array\n");
+		ret = copy_struct_from_user(&jobs[i], sizeof(*jobs),
+					    u64_to_user_ptr(args->jobs) +
+						    i * args->job_struct_size,
+					    args->job_struct_size);
+		if (ret) {
+			drm_dbg(dev, "Failed to copy incoming job array (%d)\n", ret);
 			goto exit;
 		}
 	}
 
 
-	for (i = 0; i < args->job_count; i++)
-		rocket_ioctl_submit_job(dev, file, &jobs[i]);
+	/*
+	 * Report a rejected job. The return was previously discarded, so SUBMIT
+	 * answered 0 even when a job failed validation -- userspace could not tell
+	 * a queued job from a dropped one, and every per-job check (task sizes,
+	 * regcmd_count, and any future flag validation) was unobservable. Stop at
+	 * the first failure and report it: a request the kernel cannot honor must
+	 * fail loudly, not silently. Jobs already queued keep running.
+	 */
+	for (i = 0; i < args->job_count; i++) {
+		ret = rocket_ioctl_submit_job(dev, file, &jobs[i]);
+		if (ret)
+			goto exit;
+	}
 
 exit:
 	kvfree(jobs);
-- 
2.43.0

